<dl id="n54141f"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n54" href="#n54141f">N54 (VI.B.45)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n54all.htm#n54141f"> 141(f)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> name same <small>Orange</small></blockquote> <dd class="well"> <ul class="list-inline" id="n54141f"><li>FW 28.35 </li><li><a href="../../flex/a/lexa.htm#n54141f">2010</a> </li><li><a href="../../flex/a/l39a.htm#n54141f">1939</a> </li><li><ms href="#n54141f">MS BL 47476b-469</ms> </li><li>JJA 50:275 <a name="ad8" href="../../FF/fdra/ada.htm#ad8">Usage</a> </li><li> <a href="../../flex/a/ad8.htm#n54141f">Draft: I.1&sect;1.8</a>/2.8</li> </ul> <blockquote class="sources">Chez les Canaques de la Nouvelle-Cal&eacute;donie, par exemple, il n&apos;y a pas de distinction, dans l&apos;esprit de l&apos;indig&egrave;ne, entre la personne et son nom. Le nom participe &agrave; tel point &agrave; la personne, que le nom, c&apos;est la personne elle-m&ecirc;me. Il en r&eacute;sulte que, lorsque deux personnes ont le m&ecirc;me nom, elles ont une identit&eacute; qui leur conf&egrave;re des droits pareils. <br><font color="green">[Among the Canaques of New Caledonia, for example, there is no distinction, in the mind of the native, between the person and his name. The name participates so much in the person that the name is the person himself. As a result, when two people have the same name, they have an identity that gives them similar rights.]</font> <small> Lucian L&eacute;vy-Bruhl, <a name="LBEM" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#LBEM"><cite title="source">L'exp&eacute;rience mystique</cite></a> (1938) 234</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
